(C = constant)
 x^2 + 4Cx - 2Cy = 0 
 x = \frac{-4C + \sqrt{16 C^2 - 4(-2Cy)}}{2} 
 x = 2C \left[\sqrt{1 + \frac{y}{2C}} -1\right]  
x
C
x,C > 0
x^2 + 4Cx -2Cy = x^2 + 4Cx +(2C)^2 - (2C)^2-2Cy = (x+2C)^2 - (2C)^2 \left(1 + \dfrac{y}{2C} \right) = 0
(x+2C)^2 = (2C)^2 \left(1 + \dfrac{y}{2C} \right) \implies x + 2C = \pm 2C \sqrt{\left(1 + \dfrac{y}{2C} \right)}
x = -2C \pm 2C \sqrt{\left(1 + \dfrac{y}{2C} \right)} = 2C \left( \pm \sqrt{\left(1 + \dfrac{y}{2C} \right)} - 1\right)
x = 2C \left(\sqrt{\left(1 + \dfrac{y}{2C} \right)} - 1\right)
